British Future is a UK-based think tank and registered charity whose stated aim is to advance the education of the public in the subjects of equality and diversity, human rights, racial and cultural harmony, citizenship and social inclusion.


== History ==
Incorporated in June 2011, it was initially called The Communications Organisation until was renamed British Future in December 2011. It became a charity in 2014, having been previously run as a not-for-profit organisation.
Its director is Sunder Katwala, a prominent left-wing activist and former director of the Fabian Society. He is regularly cited as an influential political thinker. British Future state that they are a non-partisan organisation.
British Future works closely with other think tanks, including Demos.


== Research and campaigns ==
In 2017, research by British Future suggested that the Conservative Party (UK) would have claimed a 42-seat majority in the 2017 general election if they had the same level of support among ethnic minority Britons as they do with white voters.It ran a campaign for shops to close, and sporting events not to be played on Remembrance Sunday 2014, ninety-six years after the ending of World War I.


== Publications ==
Its publications include This Sceptred Isle", "Team GB: How 2012 Should Boost Britain and Generation 2012: Optimism Despite Obstacles.


